[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating Java Access Helpers**\n\nI’m considering whether adding a Java source direct-access helper instead of using base64 is better. I have some doubts about calling synthetic package-private methods. Javac seems to hide those, which complicates things. I wonder about using Groovy or the ASM library, but they don’t fit either. There’s potential coverage issues with the generated helper class not marking calls correctly if the target class is already loaded. I'll need to think this through!\n\n**Analyzing Dynamic Access Reports**\n\nI’m thinking about whether the dynamic-access report uses the native-image tracing agent, which only records dynamic accesses needing config. It’s tricky if `Class.forName` is called on a class already loaded. The trace agent might skip that since no metadata is needed. To ensure coverage, I may need to access a class not already loaded, like \"io.restassured.internal.NoParameterValue,\" which seems promising. The previous test with `java.lang.String` might have been skipped due to it being a JDK class. I'll have to figure this out!\n\n**Exploring Dynamic Access Coverage**\n\nI’m considering how dynamic access coverage maps from the JSON output. If `Class.forName` targets a caller, it seems the agent records reachability metadata for classes not built into the system. If a class is already on the classpath, that might affect coverage. I wonder if targeting a library class like \"io.restassured.internal.NoParameterValue\" would help? There may be existing test files for it that aren't tracked but could still be loaded, or maybe \"io.restassured.internal.http.CharsetExtractor.\" I'll look into this!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0de81b235632784a016a013f264a408192bf12789d87114b5b\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqAT83_h7LdtownHwqTQQvEX-rHFvP1Fq_Ru6diH2Bb7hAItYGK5XgETeBEo8DhUXUM_f1-t_eWViDv84FOVjOUZa3u