eports**\\n\\nI’m thinking about whether the dynamic-access report uses the native-image tracing agent, which only records dynamic accesses needing config. It’s tricky if `Class.forName` is called on a class already loaded. The trace agent might skip that since no metadata is needed. To ensure coverage, I may need to access a class not already loaded, like \\\"io.restassured.internal.NoParameterValue,\\\" which seems promising. The previous test with `java.lang.String` might have been skipped due to it being a JDK class. I'll have to figure this out!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring Dynamic Access Coverage**\\n\\nI’m considering how dynamic access coverage maps from the JSON output. If `Class.forName` targets a caller, it seems the agent records reachability metadata for classes not built into the system. If a class is already on the classpath, that might affect coverage. I wonder if targeting a library class like \\\"io.restassured.internal.NoParameterValue\\\" would help? There may be existing test files for it that aren't tracked but could still be loaded, or maybe \\\"io.restassured.internal.http.CharsetExtractor.\\\" I'll look into this!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_PuboIVXBLEVnSRTz43oluKrC|fc_0de81b235632784a016a013f37876081928323dacb68491a76", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find /home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge8/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/source_context/io.rest-assured/rest-assured/5.5.0/main/extracted/io/restassured/internal -name '*.groovy' -o -name '*.java' | sed 's#.*/extracted/##;s#/#.#g;s#\\.groovy$##;s#\\.java$##' | sort | sed -n '1,120p'", "timeout": 30}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1263, "output": 1323, "cacheRead": 110592, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 113178, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778466596371, "responseId": "resp_0de81b235632